<TITLE> Top US general in Afghanistan sacked </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 By Arshad Mahmud in Washington May 11 (bdnews24.com)The Obama administration on Monday fired the most senior American general commanding the NATO forces in Afghanistan only a year after he was appointed to that post. The abrupt sacking of Gen. David McKiernan caught the most seasoned military analysts in Washington by surprise as it is rare in American history to remove a wartime commander, and especially at time when the country appears to be spiraling downward. In the past, only a handful of times such a senior, decorated general has been relived of his duties in the midst of war. In 1951, President Harry Truman removed Gen. Douglas MacArthur while he was still commanding the allied forces in Europe after the Second World War. While no reason was given for the general's removal, defence secretary Robert Gates said that the administration thought it would be better to bring changes at the top of the military leadership in Afghanistan in the face of rising concern over the country's deteriorating situat
